items.text: I often get so absorbed in my own thoughts that I lose track of what's happening around me.
items.rationale: Being absorbed in internal thought and losing awareness of surroundings is a core marker of high Abstractedness.

items.text: My mind tends to wander during conversations, drifting to unrelated ideas.
items.rationale: Mind-wandering and imaginative drifting are hallmark indicators of Abstractedness.

items.text: People sometimes tell me I seem to be in my own world.
items.rationale: Third-person observation of being detached from immediate reality reflects high Abstractedness.

items.text: I find myself daydreaming about possibilities rather than focusing on what's right in front of me.
items.rationale: Preference for imaginative possibilities over concrete present reality is central to Abstractedness.

items.text: I am more interested in ideas and concepts than in practical, hands-on tasks.
items.rationale: Preference for abstract ideation over practical engagement directly taps Abstractedness.

items.text: When solving a problem, I tend to think in terms of broad patterns rather than specific details.
items.rationale: A global, pattern-oriented cognitive style is characteristic of high Abstractedness.

items.text: I sometimes forget appointments or daily tasks because my mind is elsewhere.
items.rationale: Absent-mindedness due to internal preoccupation is a behavioral consequence of high Abstractedness.

items.text: I enjoy letting my imagination run free without any particular goal in mind.
items.rationale: Undirected imaginative activity is a direct expression of Abstractedness.

items.text: Others would describe me as a dreamer rather than a doer.
items.rationale: The dreamer-versus-doer distinction captures the essence of high versus low Abstractedness.

items.text: I often think about theoretical questions that most people would consider impractical.
items.rationale: Engagement with impractical theoretical questions reflects a highly abstract cognitive orientation.

items.text: I can spend hours lost in thought without feeling bored.
items.rationale: Sustained internal ideation without restlessness is a strong indicator of Abstractedness.

items.text: I tend to overlook practical details because I'm focused on the bigger picture.
items.rationale: Neglecting concrete details in favor of overarching ideas is characteristic of high Abstractedness.

items.text: I sometimes have creative insights that seem to come out of nowhere while I'm doing something routine.
items.rationale: Spontaneous creative insights suggest an active inner life, though this could also relate to Openness to Change.

items.text: I prefer reading about philosophical ideas over reading practical how-to guides.
items.rationale: Preference for philosophical content suggests Abstractedness, but could also reflect Reasoning or intellectual curiosity.

items.text: I enjoy exploring new and unconventional ideas just for the sake of thinking about them.
items.rationale: Exploring unconventional ideas overlaps with Openness to Change; the 'just for thinking' aspect leans toward Abstractedness but the novelty-seeking aspect could indicate Openness to Change.

items.text: I frequently worry that I've said or done the wrong thing in social situations.
items.rationale: Ruminating over social missteps is a core expression of Apprehension (guilt-proneness and self-doubt).

items.text: I tend to feel guilty even when I know I haven't done anything wrong.
items.rationale: Irrational guilt is one of the defining features of high Apprehension in the 16PF.

items.text: I often second-guess my decisions long after I've made them.
items.rationale: Persistent self-doubt and post-decisional rumination are hallmarks of Apprehension.

items.text: I have a nagging sense that things could go wrong, even when everything seems fine.
items.rationale: A pervasive sense of impending trouble reflects the worry and insecurity central to Apprehension.

items.text: I am harder on myself than most people are on themselves.
items.rationale: Excessive self-criticism is a direct behavioral indicator of high Apprehension.

items.text: When someone criticizes me, I dwell on it for days.
items.rationale: Prolonged rumination over criticism reflects the self-doubt and sensitivity characteristic of Apprehension.

items.text: I often feel insecure about whether I'm good enough at what I do.
items.rationale: Chronic self-doubt about competence is a core feature of high Apprehension.

items.text: I worry about making mistakes more than most people seem to.
items.rationale: Excessive worry about errors reflects the anxious, self-doubting nature of Apprehension.

items.text: Even small failures leave me feeling deeply disappointed in myself.
items.rationale: Disproportionate self-disappointment over minor failures is characteristic of high Apprehension.

items.text: I sometimes lie awake at night replaying things I wish I had handled differently.
items.rationale: Nighttime rumination about past actions is a strong behavioral marker of Apprehension.

items.text: I feel a sense of unease in new situations, as if I might not measure up.
items.rationale: Anticipatory self-doubt in novel contexts reflects the insecurity central to Apprehension.

items.text: Others have told me I apologize too much.
items.rationale: Excessive apologizing is a behavioral manifestation of guilt-proneness and self-blame in Apprehension.

items.text: I find it difficult to let go of past mistakes and move on.
items.rationale: Difficulty releasing past mistakes suggests Apprehension, though it could also relate to low Emotional Stability.

items.text: I sometimes feel anxious without being able to identify a specific reason.
items.rationale: Free-floating anxiety is consistent with Apprehension but overlaps with low Emotional Stability.

items.text: I get easily upset when things don't go as planned, and I blame myself for not preparing better.
items.rationale: The self-blame component maps to Apprehension, but getting easily upset when plans fail could also indicate low Emotional Stability.

items.text: I naturally take charge when a group needs direction.
items.rationale: Spontaneously assuming leadership is a core behavioral expression of high Dominance.

items.text: I am comfortable telling others what to do and expect them to follow through.
items.rationale: Comfort with directing others and expecting compliance is central to Dominance.

items.text: In disagreements, I stand my ground firmly and rarely back down.
items.rationale: Assertiveness and persistence in conflict are hallmark features of high Dominance.

items.text: I prefer to be the one making decisions rather than deferring to someone else.
items.rationale: Preference for decision-making authority directly reflects Dominance.

items.text: People often look to me to settle disputes or make the final call.
items.rationale: Being sought out as an authority figure reflects the social influence associated with Dominance.

items.text: I don't hesitate to challenge someone's opinion if I think they're wrong.
items.rationale: Willingness to confront and challenge others is a direct expression of Dominance.

items.text: I feel frustrated when I have to follow rules or procedures that I didn't help create.
items.rationale: Frustration with externally imposed constraints reflects the autonomy-seeking aspect of Dominance.

items.text: I enjoy persuading others to see things my way.
items.rationale: Enjoyment of persuasion and influence is a core motivational component of Dominance.

items.text: When working in a team, I usually end up organizing everyone's roles.
items.rationale: Taking on the organizing role in groups is a behavioral indicator of high Dominance.

items.text: I am not afraid to voice an unpopular opinion in a meeting.
items.rationale: Willingness to express dissenting views publicly reflects the assertiveness of Dominance.

items.text: I would rather lead a project than be a team member following someone else's plan.
items.rationale: Preference for leadership over followership is a straightforward indicator of Dominance.

items.text: Others have described me as forceful or commanding in how I communicate.
items.rationale: Being perceived as forceful or commanding is a third-person observation consistent with high Dominance.

items.text: I feel confident expressing my needs and expectations to others, even in tense situations.
items.rationale: Confident self-expression in tense situations suggests Dominance, though it could also reflect high Emotional Stability.

items.text: I tend to take control of situations because I trust my own judgment more than others'.
items.rationale: Taking control based on self-trust maps to Dominance, but the self-trust element could also reflect Emotional Stability or self-assurance.

items.text: I have strong opinions and I'm not shy about sharing them, which sometimes rubs people the wrong way.
items.rationale: Strong opinion-sharing maps to Dominance, but the interpersonal friction could also suggest low Privateness (forthright, genuine) or low sensitivity to social norms.

items.text: I can handle stressful situations without becoming overwhelmed or panicked.
items.rationale: Maintaining composure under stress is a defining feature of high Emotional Stability (Factor C).

items.text: My mood stays fairly consistent from day to day; I don't experience dramatic emotional swings.
items.rationale: Mood consistency and absence of emotional volatility are core indicators of Emotional Stability.

items.text: When things go wrong, I can usually keep my emotions in check and think clearly.
items.rationale: Emotional regulation during adversity is a hallmark of high Emotional Stability.

items.text: I rarely feel overwhelmed by my feelings.
items.rationale: Not being overwhelmed by emotions directly reflects the ego strength captured by Emotional Stability.

items.text: I recover quickly from setbacks and disappointments.
items.rationale: Rapid emotional recovery is a behavioral marker of high Emotional Stability.

items.text: I feel emotionally grounded and secure in who I am.
items.rationale: A sense of emotional groundedness and self-security is central to Emotional Stability.

items.text: I don't get easily irritated or frustrated by minor inconveniences.
items.rationale: Tolerance for minor frustrations without irritability reflects high Emotional Stability.

items.text: People around me would say I'm calm and level-headed, even in a crisis.
items.rationale: Being perceived as calm in crises is a strong third-person indicator of Emotional Stability.

items.text: I feel capable of dealing with most of life's challenges without excessive worry.
items.rationale: Self-efficacy in facing challenges without excessive worry reflects the adaptive coping of Emotional Stability.

items.text: I don't tend to dwell on negative experiences for very long.
items.rationale: Low rumination on negative events is characteristic of high Emotional Stability.

items.text: I can separate my personal feelings from the decisions I need to make.
items.rationale: Ability to compartmentalize emotions from decision-making reflects strong ego strength.

items.text: I generally feel satisfied with my life and don't experience persistent dissatisfaction.
items.rationale: General life satisfaction and absence of chronic dissatisfaction are associated with high Emotional Stability.

items.text: I can accept criticism without it deeply affecting my self-worth.
items.rationale: Resilience to criticism suggests Emotional Stability, but also overlaps with low Apprehension.

items.text: I feel confident that I can manage whatever life throws at me.
items.rationale: Generalized self-confidence in coping maps to Emotional Stability but could also reflect Dominance-related self-assurance.

items.text: I don't worry much about what other people think of me, and I feel secure in my own skin.
items.rationale: Not worrying about others' opinions suggests Emotional Stability, but the social evaluation component could also indicate low Apprehension.

items.text: I love being the life of the party and making everyone laugh.
items.rationale: Enjoying being the center of social attention and entertaining others is a core expression of Liveliness.

items.text: I have a lot of energy and enthusiasm that others find infectious.
items.rationale: High energy and contagious enthusiasm are defining features of Liveliness (Factor F).

items.text: I tend to act spontaneously rather than carefully planning everything out.
items.rationale: Spontaneity and impulsiveness are characteristic of high Liveliness.

items.text: I get bored easily if things become too routine or predictable.
items.rationale: Low tolerance for routine and need for stimulation are hallmarks of Liveliness.

items.text: I am usually cheerful and upbeat, even when others around me are serious.
items.rationale: Persistent cheerfulness regardless of social context is a strong indicator of high Liveliness.

items.text: I enjoy taking risks and trying new things just for the thrill of it.
items.rationale: Thrill-seeking and risk-taking for excitement are behavioral expressions of Liveliness.

items.text: My friends would describe me as fun-loving and carefree.
items.rationale: Being perceived as fun-loving and carefree is a third-person marker of high Liveliness.

items.text: I find it hard to sit still for long periods; I always want to be doing something active.
items.rationale: Restlessness and preference for activity over stillness reflect the high energy of Liveliness.

items.text: I often speak before I think, which sometimes gets me into trouble.
items.rationale: Impulsive speech is a behavioral consequence of the spontaneous, uninhibited nature of high Liveliness.

items.text: I prefer social gatherings over quiet evenings at home.
items.rationale: Preference for social stimulation over solitude is consistent with the surgent, outgoing quality of Liveliness.

items.text: I laugh easily and find humor in most situations.
items.rationale: Ready laughter and pervasive humor appreciation are characteristic of high Liveliness.

items.text: I would rather do something exciting and unplanned than follow a set schedule.
items.rationale: Preference for excitement over structure reflects the impulsive, stimulation-seeking nature of Liveliness.

items.text: I sometimes struggle to take serious matters as seriously as I should because I default to humor.
items.rationale: Defaulting to humor in serious situations suggests Liveliness, though it could also reflect a coping mechanism related to Emotional Stability.

items.text: I feel restless and dissatisfied when my life lacks variety and excitement.
items.rationale: Need for variety maps to Liveliness, but dissatisfaction with routine could also relate to Openness to Change.

items.text: I'm always eager to try the latest trend or experience something I've never done before.
items.rationale: Eagerness for new experiences maps to Liveliness through novelty-seeking, but also strongly overlaps with Openness to Change.

items.text: I actively seek out new experiences and enjoy experimenting with different ways of doing things.
items.rationale: Actively seeking novelty and experimentation is a core expression of Openness to Change (Factor Q1).

items.text: I believe that traditions should be questioned and updated when they no longer serve a purpose.
items.rationale: Willingness to challenge and revise traditions is central to high Openness to Change.

items.text: I get excited about innovative ideas and new approaches to old problems.
items.rationale: Enthusiasm for innovation and novel problem-solving directly reflects Openness to Change.

items.text: I would rather try an untested method than stick with a proven but outdated one.
items.rationale: Preference for untested methods over established ones is a strong indicator of Openness to Change.

items.text: I find it stimulating to debate ideas that challenge conventional thinking.
items.rationale: Enjoying intellectual debate that challenges norms reflects the critical, progressive orientation of Openness to Change.

items.text: I think society benefits most when people are willing to embrace change rather than resist it.
items.rationale: A philosophical stance favoring societal change is a direct attitudinal marker of Openness to Change.

items.text: I quickly grow impatient with people who refuse to consider new perspectives.
items.rationale: Impatience with closed-mindedness reflects the value placed on intellectual flexibility in Openness to Change.

items.text: I enjoy reading about cutting-edge developments in science, technology, or culture.
items.rationale: Interest in cutting-edge developments reflects the progressive, novelty-oriented nature of Openness to Change.

items.text: I am comfortable with ambiguity and don't need everything to be settled or certain.
items.rationale: Tolerance for ambiguity is associated with the flexible, change-embracing orientation of this factor.

items.text: I often question established rules and wonder if there's a better way to do things.
items.rationale: Questioning established rules and seeking improvements is a hallmark of high Openness to Change.

items.text: I would describe myself as progressive and forward-thinking in my views.
items.rationale: Self-identification as progressive directly maps to the liberal, change-oriented pole of this factor.

items.text: I believe that clinging to the past holds people back from reaching their potential.
items.rationale: Viewing attachment to the past as limiting reflects the forward-looking orientation of Openness to Change.

items.text: I like to explore different cultures and ways of life because they broaden my understanding of the world.
items.rationale: Cultural exploration suggests Openness to Change, though it could also reflect Abstractedness or general intellectual curiosity.

items.text: I feel energized when I'm learning something completely new and unfamiliar.
items.rationale: Energization from novelty maps to Openness to Change, but the learning component could also relate to Reasoning.

items.text: I spend a lot of time thinking about how things could be improved or reimagined.
items.rationale: Thinking about improvements maps to Openness to Change, but the contemplative, idea-focused quality could also indicate Abstractedness.

items.text: I set very high standards for myself and feel dissatisfied when my work falls short of them.
items.rationale: Setting high personal standards and dissatisfaction with imperfection are core features of Perfectionism (Factor Q3).

items.text: I like to have everything organized and in its proper place before I begin a task.
items.rationale: Need for order and organization before starting work is a hallmark of high Perfectionism.

items.text: I pay close attention to details and double-check my work for errors.
items.rationale: Meticulous attention to detail and error-checking are direct behavioral indicators of Perfectionism.

items.text: I believe that if something is worth doing, it's worth doing right.
items.rationale: This attitude reflects the high standards and commitment to quality central to Perfectionism.

items.text: I feel uncomfortable leaving a task unfinished or in a messy state.
items.rationale: Discomfort with incompleteness or disorder is characteristic of high Perfectionism.

items.text: I plan my activities carefully and follow through on my plans in an orderly way.
items.rationale: Careful planning and orderly follow-through are behavioral expressions of Perfectionism.

items.text: Others would say I am disciplined and self-controlled in how I approach my responsibilities.
items.rationale: Being perceived as disciplined and self-controlled is a third-person indicator of high Perfectionism.

items.text: I keep my living and working spaces neat and well-organized.
items.rationale: Maintaining orderly environments is a concrete behavioral marker of Perfectionism.

items.text: I get frustrated when other people are careless or sloppy in their work.
items.rationale: Frustration with others' carelessness reflects the high standards that perfectionistic individuals apply broadly.

items.text: I always try to present myself in a polished and put-together manner.
items.rationale: Concern with self-presentation and appearing polished reflects the self-image control aspect of Perfectionism.

items.text: I make lists and schedules to ensure I stay on track with my goals.
items.rationale: Using lists and schedules for goal management is a practical expression of the organized, controlled nature of Perfectionism.

items.text: I take pride in being thorough and precise in everything I do.
items.rationale: Pride in thoroughness and precision directly reflects the quality-oriented nature of Perfectionism.

items.text: I sometimes spend more time than necessary perfecting something because I can't let go of small imperfections.
items.rationale: Over-investing time in perfecting work suggests Perfectionism, though the inability to let go could also relate to Apprehension.

items.text: I feel a strong need to be in control of my environment and how things are done.
items.rationale: Need for environmental control maps to Perfectionism, but the control aspect could also overlap with Dominance.

items.text: I insist on following proper procedures and doing things by the book, even when shortcuts are available.
items.rationale: Insistence on proper procedures maps to Perfectionism through orderliness, but adherence to established rules also strongly suggests Rule-Consciousness.

items.text: I keep my personal feelings and private life to myself, even around close friends.
items.rationale: Withholding personal information even from close others is a defining feature of high Privateness (Factor N).

items.text: I am careful about what I reveal about myself to others.
items.rationale: Deliberate self-disclosure management is a core expression of Privateness.

items.text: I tend to present a polished image to the world that may differ from how I truly feel inside.
items.rationale: Maintaining a curated public image that differs from inner experience reflects the shrewd, guarded nature of Privateness.

items.text: I don't like it when people ask me personal questions.
items.rationale: Discomfort with personal inquiries is a direct indicator of high Privateness.

items.text: I am good at reading social situations and adjusting what I say accordingly.
items.rationale: Social astuteness and strategic self-presentation are hallmarks of high Privateness (shrewdness).

items.text: I rarely share my true opinions unless I'm sure it's safe to do so.
items.rationale: Withholding opinions until safety is assured reflects the guarded, calculating nature of Privateness.

items.text: People who know me casually would be surprised by how different I am in private.
items.rationale: A significant gap between public and private self is characteristic of high Privateness.

items.text: I think it's unwise to be completely open with people because it gives them power over you.
items.rationale: Viewing openness as a vulnerability reflects the strategic, self-protective orientation of Privateness.

items.text: I prefer to observe and listen in social situations rather than share about myself.
items.rationale: Preferring observation over self-disclosure in social settings is a behavioral marker of Privateness.

items.text: I am skilled at keeping a poker face and not letting others know what I'm really thinking.
items.rationale: Emotional concealment and inscrutability are core features of high Privateness.

items.text: I find it easy to be diplomatic and tactful, even when I disagree with someone.
items.rationale: Diplomatic tact, especially when concealing disagreement, reflects the social shrewdness of Privateness.

items.text: I would rather deal with my problems on my own than burden others with them.
items.rationale: Preference for handling problems privately rather than seeking support reflects high Privateness.

items.text: I sometimes feel lonely because I find it hard to let people truly know me.
items.rationale: Loneliness from self-concealment suggests Privateness, but the emotional distress component could also relate to low Emotional Stability or Apprehension.

items.text: I am very selective about who I consider a true friend and let into my inner circle.
items.rationale: Selectivity in close relationships maps to Privateness, though it could also reflect general cautiousness or low trust.

items.text: I carefully think through what I'm going to say before I speak, especially in important conversations.
items.rationale: Careful verbal planning maps to Privateness through strategic communication, but could also reflect Perfectionism's controlled, deliberate approach.

items.text: I enjoy solving complex logical puzzles and brain teasers.
items.rationale: Enjoyment of logical puzzles directly taps the abstract reasoning and intellectual problem-solving of Factor B.

items.text: I can quickly identify patterns and relationships in data or information.
items.rationale: Rapid pattern recognition is a core cognitive ability associated with high Reasoning.

items.text: I find it easy to follow complex arguments and identify logical flaws.
items.rationale: Ability to track complex arguments and detect logical errors is a direct indicator of Reasoning ability.

items.text: I am good at figuring out how things work by analyzing their components.
items.rationale: Analytical decomposition of systems reflects the systematic thinking characteristic of high Reasoning.

items.text: I learn new concepts quickly and can apply them to unfamiliar situations.
items.rationale: Rapid concept acquisition and transfer to novel contexts are hallmarks of high Reasoning.

items.text: When presented with a problem, I naturally break it down into smaller, manageable parts.
items.rationale: Systematic problem decomposition is a behavioral expression of strong analytical reasoning.

items.text: I can usually see the logical consequences of a decision before others do.
items.rationale: Anticipating logical consequences reflects the forward-thinking analytical capacity of high Reasoning.

items.text: I prefer explanations that are based on evidence and logic rather than intuition or feeling.
items.rationale: Preference for evidence-based, logical explanations over intuitive ones reflects the rational orientation of Reasoning.

items.text: I am comfortable working with numbers, statistics, and quantitative information.
items.rationale: Comfort with quantitative information is associated with the cognitive proficiency captured by Reasoning.

items.text: Others often come to me when they need help thinking through a complicated problem.
items.rationale: Being sought out for complex problem-solving is a third-person indicator of high Reasoning.

items.text: I can hold multiple pieces of information in mind simultaneously and see how they connect.
items.rationale: Working memory capacity and integrative thinking are cognitive markers of high Reasoning.

items.text: I enjoy intellectual challenges that require sustained concentration and careful thought.
items.rationale: Enjoyment of intellectually demanding tasks requiring concentration reflects high Reasoning.

items.text: I tend to approach decisions analytically, weighing pros and cons before committing.
items.rationale: Analytical decision-making suggests Reasoning, but the deliberate weighing process could also reflect Perfectionism.

items.text: I am drawn to subjects like mathematics, philosophy, or science because they require rigorous thinking.
items.rationale: Attraction to rigorous intellectual disciplines suggests Reasoning, though it could also reflect Abstractedness or Openness to Change.

items.text: I enjoy thinking about abstract theoretical problems that don't have obvious practical applications.
items.rationale: Engagement with abstract theoretical problems maps to Reasoning through intellectual capacity, but the abstract, impractical quality strongly overlaps with Abstractedness.

items.text: I believe it's important to follow rules and regulations, even when no one is watching.
items.rationale: Adherence to rules regardless of external monitoring is a defining feature of Rule-Consciousness (Factor G).

items.text: I have a strong sense of duty and always try to fulfill my obligations.
items.rationale: A strong sense of duty and obligation fulfillment is central to high Rule-Consciousness.

items.text: I feel uncomfortable when I see people bending or breaking rules, even minor ones.
items.rationale: Discomfort with rule-breaking by others reflects the moral conscientiousness of this factor.

items.text: I always try to do what is morally right, even when it's difficult or inconvenient.
items.rationale: Commitment to moral behavior despite difficulty is a hallmark of high Rule-Consciousness.

items.text: I respect authority and believe that social structures exist for good reasons.
items.rationale: Respect for authority and social structures reflects the conforming, dutiful nature of Rule-Consciousness.

items.text: I would never cheat on a test or cut corners at work, even if I knew I wouldn't get caught.
items.rationale: Refusal to cheat regardless of detection risk reflects internalized moral standards characteristic of Rule-Consciousness.

items.text: I feel a strong responsibility to keep my promises and commitments.
items.rationale: Commitment to promise-keeping reflects the dependability and moral obligation central to Rule-Consciousness.

items.text: I think people should be held accountable for their actions and face consequences when they break rules.
items.rationale: Belief in accountability and consequences for rule-breaking reflects the justice-oriented aspect of Rule-Consciousness.

items.text: I was raised to respect the law and I carry those values with me as an adult.
items.rationale: Internalized respect for law from upbringing reflects the socialized, conforming nature of Rule-Consciousness.

items.text: I feel guilty when I fail to meet my responsibilities, even if the failure was beyond my control.
items.rationale: Guilt over unmet responsibilities, even when uncontrollable, reflects the strong superego associated with Rule-Consciousness.

items.text: I believe that maintaining social order and following established norms is essential for a functioning society.
items.rationale: Valuing social order and norms is a direct attitudinal expression of Rule-Consciousness.

items.text: I am the kind of person who returns extra change if a cashier gives me too much.
items.rationale: Honest behavior in low-stakes situations where dishonesty would go unnoticed is a strong behavioral marker of Rule-Consciousness.

items.text: I sometimes struggle with situations where the right thing to do isn't clearly defined by any rule.
items.rationale: Difficulty in ambiguous moral situations suggests reliance on external rules characteristic of Rule-Consciousness, but could also relate to low Openness to Change.

items.text: I prefer working in environments with clear expectations and well-defined procedures.
items.rationale: Preference for clear expectations maps to Rule-Consciousness, but could also reflect Perfectionism's need for structure.

items.text: I feel uneasy when I haven't completed all my tasks for the day, as if I've let someone down.
items.rationale: Unease over incomplete tasks maps to Rule-Consciousness through duty, but the guilt and self-blame component could also indicate Apprehension.

items.text: I prefer to work through problems on my own rather than asking others for help.
items.rationale: Preference for independent problem-solving is a core marker of self-reliance (Factor Q2).

items.text: When making important decisions, I trust my own judgment above anyone else's advice.
items.rationale: Trusting one's own judgment over external input directly reflects autonomous decision-making.

items.text: I am most productive when I can work alone without interruptions.
items.rationale: Preference for solitary work conditions is characteristic of high self-reliance.

items.text: I rarely feel the need to consult with others before taking action.
items.rationale: Low need for consultation reflects autonomous functioning central to self-reliance.

items.text: People describe me as someone who likes to do things independently.
items.rationale: Third-person observation of independent behavior is a direct indicator of self-reliance.

items.text: I would rather figure something out myself than attend a group training session.
items.rationale: Choosing self-directed learning over group instruction reflects preference for autonomy.

items.text: I don't mind spending long stretches of time entirely on my own.
items.rationale: Comfort with extended solitude is a behavioral hallmark of self-reliance.

items.text: I feel somewhat burdened when others depend on me to make group decisions.
items.rationale: Discomfort with group dependency roles reflects preference for individual rather than collective functioning.

items.text: When I travel, I prefer to plan my own itinerary rather than join a guided tour.
items.rationale: Choosing self-directed travel over group-guided experiences reflects autonomous preference.

items.text: I find group brainstorming sessions less effective than thinking things through alone.
items.rationale: Valuing solitary ideation over collaborative processes is a clear self-reliance indicator.

items.text: I have always been the kind of person who charts my own course in life.
items.rationale: Self-described autonomous life navigation is a direct expression of self-reliance.

items.text: I seldom seek reassurance from friends or family when I'm uncertain about something.
items.rationale: Low reassurance-seeking behavior under uncertainty reflects internal locus of support.

items.text: I sometimes feel disconnected from others because I handle everything myself.
items.rationale: While reflecting self-reliance, the emotional disconnection component introduces some ambiguity with low warmth.

items.text: I find it hard to delegate tasks because I believe I can do them better myself.
items.rationale: Difficulty delegating reflects self-reliance but could also indicate perfectionism or low trust (vigilance).

items.text: I keep my problems to myself because I don't think others would truly understand.
items.rationale: While self-contained coping reflects self-reliance, the belief that others won't understand could also indicate high vigilance (suspicion/distrust).

items.text: I am easily moved by music, art, or a beautiful sunset.
items.rationale: Aesthetic emotional responsiveness is a core facet of sensitivity (Factor I).

items.text: I tend to be deeply affected by the emotions of people around me.
items.rationale: Emotional contagion and empathic responsiveness are central to high sensitivity.

items.text: I find myself tearing up during movies or when reading a touching story.
items.rationale: Emotional reactivity to narrative content is a behavioral marker of sensitivity.

items.text: I value beauty and elegance in my surroundings more than most people seem to.
items.rationale: Heightened aesthetic appreciation is a defining characteristic of the sensitivity factor.

items.text: People sometimes tell me I'm too tender-hearted for my own good.
items.rationale: Third-person feedback about excessive tenderness directly reflects high sensitivity.

items.text: I believe that kindness and compassion matter more than efficiency and results.
items.rationale: Prioritizing compassion over utilitarian outcomes reflects the refined, feeling-oriented nature of sensitivity.

items.text: I have a rich inner emotional life that I don't always share with others.
items.rationale: A deep, complex emotional inner world is characteristic of high sensitivity.

items.text: Harsh or crude behavior from others genuinely upsets me.
items.rationale: Distress in response to coarseness reflects the refined, delicate temperament of high sensitivity.

items.text: I often notice subtle emotional shifts in others that most people miss.
items.rationale: Fine-grained emotional perception is a hallmark of the sensitive temperament.

items.text: I would rather read poetry than a technical manual.
items.rationale: Preference for aesthetic-emotional content over utilitarian material reflects sensitivity.

items.text: I feel a deep sense of sympathy when I see someone struggling, even a stranger.
items.rationale: Broad empathic concern extending to strangers is a clear marker of high sensitivity.

items.text: I am drawn to experiences that stir deep feelings, even if they are bittersweet.
items.rationale: Seeking emotionally evocative experiences reflects the feeling-oriented nature of sensitivity.

items.text: I sometimes feel overwhelmed by the suffering I see in the world.
items.rationale: While emotional overwhelm from suffering reflects sensitivity, the overwhelm component could also relate to tension.

items.text: I need time to recover emotionally after witnessing conflict between people.
items.rationale: Emotional recovery needs after conflict exposure reflect sensitivity but could also indicate tension or low social boldness.

items.text: I worry a lot about whether I've hurt someone's feelings without realizing it.
items.rationale: While concern about others' feelings reflects sensitivity, the worry and rumination component could map to tension (Factor Q4).

items.text: I enjoy being the center of attention at social gatherings.
items.rationale: Comfort and pleasure in being the social focal point is a core marker of social boldness (Factor H).

items.text: I have no trouble speaking up in a room full of strangers.
items.rationale: Ease of verbal assertion in unfamiliar social contexts directly reflects social boldness.

items.text: I volunteer to lead group discussions or presentations whenever I can.
items.rationale: Actively seeking leadership in public-facing roles is a behavioral indicator of high social boldness.

items.text: Meeting new people energizes me rather than drains me.
items.rationale: Social approach motivation and energy gain from novel social contact reflect social boldness.

items.text: I rarely feel nervous before giving a speech or presentation.
items.rationale: Low performance anxiety in public speaking situations is a hallmark of social boldness.

items.text: I find it easy to walk up to someone I don't know and start a conversation.
items.rationale: Initiating contact with strangers without hesitation is a direct behavioral expression of social boldness.

items.text: Others would describe me as thick-skinned when it comes to social situations.
items.rationale: Social resilience and low threat sensitivity in interpersonal contexts reflect the venturesome quality of social boldness.

items.text: I thrive in situations that require me to think on my feet in front of others.
items.rationale: Comfort with spontaneous public performance reflects the adventurous, uninhibited nature of social boldness.

items.text: I am usually the first person to break the ice in an awkward social situation.
items.rationale: Taking initiative to resolve social discomfort reflects confidence and low social threat sensitivity.

items.text: I feel comfortable challenging authority figures when I disagree with them.
items.rationale: Willingness to confront authority reflects the fearlessness and assertiveness of social boldness.

items.text: Large social events feel like opportunities rather than obligations to me.
items.rationale: Positive appraisal of large social gatherings reflects the approach-oriented nature of social boldness.

items.text: I don't hesitate to share my opinions even when they might be unpopular.
items.rationale: Expressing potentially controversial views without hesitation reflects social fearlessness.

items.text: I enjoy taking risks in social situations, like telling jokes to a tough crowd.
items.rationale: Social risk-taking reflects boldness, though the risk-seeking element could also relate to general impulsivity.

items.text: I get a rush from performing or presenting in front of large audiences.
items.rationale: While the performance enjoyment reflects social boldness, the 'rush' component could suggest sensation-seeking beyond the core factor.

items.text: I naturally take charge in group settings because I'm comfortable directing others.
items.rationale: While comfort directing others reflects social boldness, the dominance and control aspects could map to Dominance (Factor E).

items.text: I often feel restless and on edge, even when there's no obvious reason.
items.rationale: Free-floating restlessness and agitation are core markers of tension (Factor Q4).

items.text: I have difficulty relaxing even when I have nothing pressing to do.
items.rationale: Inability to relax during downtime directly reflects the driven, wound-up quality of high tension.

items.text: I frequently feel frustrated that things aren't moving fast enough.
items.rationale: Chronic impatience and frustration with pace reflect the pent-up energy characteristic of tension.

items.text: My mind races with thoughts and worries, especially at night.
items.rationale: Ruminative thought patterns and nocturnal worry are hallmark expressions of high tension.

items.text: I carry a lot of physical tension in my body, like tight shoulders or a clenched jaw.
items.rationale: Somatic manifestations of psychological tension directly reflect the factor.

items.text: Small annoyances bother me more than they probably should.
items.rationale: Disproportionate irritability to minor stressors reflects the low frustration tolerance of high tension.

items.text: I feel like I'm always under pressure, even when my workload is manageable.
items.rationale: Subjective experience of pressure independent of objective demands is a core tension indicator.

items.text: I have trouble sitting still for long periods because of an inner sense of urgency.
items.rationale: Psychomotor restlessness driven by internal urgency is a behavioral marker of high tension.

items.text: People close to me say I need to learn to unwind and let things go.
items.rationale: Third-person observation of inability to relax is a direct indicator of high tension.

items.text: I often feel a sense of dissatisfaction, as though something important is unresolved.
items.rationale: Chronic dissatisfaction and sense of incompleteness reflect the frustrated, driven quality of tension.

items.text: I tend to snap at people when I'm under stress, even when they don't deserve it.
items.rationale: Irritable outbursts under stress reflect the low frustration tolerance and pent-up energy of tension.

items.text: I find it very hard to be patient when I'm waiting for something important.
items.rationale: Difficulty tolerating anticipatory waiting reflects the driven, impatient quality of high tension.

items.text: I sometimes feel anxious about things that haven't happened yet and may never happen.
items.rationale: Anticipatory anxiety reflects tension but could also overlap with general anxiety or apprehension (Factor O).

items.text: I have a hard time forgiving myself when I make a mistake, and it eats at me for days.
items.rationale: Persistent self-directed frustration reflects tension, though the self-critical element could also relate to apprehension (Factor O).

items.text: I lie awake at night replaying conversations and wondering if people were being honest with me.
items.rationale: While the restlessness and rumination reflect tension, the focus on others' honesty could map to vigilance (Factor L).

items.text: I tend to question people's motives, even when they appear to be acting kindly.
items.rationale: Suspicion of others' motives despite positive behavior is a core marker of vigilance (Factor L).

items.text: I find it hard to take people at face value; I always look for the hidden agenda.
items.rationale: Habitual search for hidden agendas directly reflects the suspicious, watchful quality of vigilance.

items.text: I keep a mental record of times people have let me down or treated me unfairly.
items.rationale: Tracking interpersonal grievances reflects the grudge-holding, distrustful nature of high vigilance.

items.text: When someone gives me a compliment, my first thought is to wonder what they want from me.
items.rationale: Interpreting positive social gestures as instrumental reflects core suspiciousness.

items.text: I am very careful about who I trust with personal information.
items.rationale: Guarded information sharing reflects the cautious, self-protective stance of high vigilance.

items.text: I believe that most people will take advantage of you if you give them the chance.
items.rationale: A generalized belief in others' exploitative nature is a defining feature of high vigilance.

items.text: I pay close attention to inconsistencies in what people say and do.
items.rationale: Monitoring for behavioral inconsistencies reflects the watchful, skeptical quality of vigilance.

items.text: I have been told that I am too suspicious of other people's intentions.
items.rationale: Third-person feedback about excessive suspiciousness is a direct indicator of high vigilance.

items.text: It takes me a very long time to fully trust someone new in my life.
items.rationale: Slow trust development reflects the guarded, cautious interpersonal style of high vigilance.

items.text: I often feel that people are talking about me behind my back.
items.rationale: Suspicion of covert social evaluation is a classic expression of high vigilance.

items.text: When something goes wrong in a group project, I suspect someone isn't pulling their weight on purpose.
items.rationale: Attributing group failures to deliberate sabotage reflects the suspicious attribution style of vigilance.

items.text: I double-check information people give me because I've learned not to rely on others' accuracy.
items.rationale: Habitual verification of others' claims reflects distrust and skepticism central to vigilance.

items.text: I am slow to forgive people who have wronged me, even if they apologize sincerely.
items.rationale: Difficulty forgiving reflects vigilance's grudge-holding quality, though it could also relate to low warmth or agreeableness.

items.text: I prefer to observe a new group for a while before participating, to figure out the dynamics.
items.rationale: Strategic social observation reflects vigilance, but could also indicate low social boldness or shyness.

items.text: I prefer to handle things on my own because I don't trust others to do them right.
items.rationale: While distrust of others' competence reflects vigilance, the preference for independent action could also map to self-reliance (Factor Q2).

items.text: I genuinely enjoy making people feel welcome and comfortable.
items.rationale: Deriving pleasure from creating comfort for others is a core expression of warmth (Factor A).

items.text: I find it easy to express affection toward the people I care about.
items.rationale: Ease of affectionate expression is a direct behavioral marker of high warmth.

items.text: I am the kind of person who remembers people's birthdays and checks in on friends regularly.
items.rationale: Proactive social maintenance behaviors reflect the attentive, caring quality of warmth.

items.text: People often come to me when they need someone to talk to because I'm approachable.
items.rationale: Being sought out as a confidant due to approachability reflects the interpersonal attractiveness of high warmth.

items.text: I feel a strong sense of connection with others, even people I've just met.
items.rationale: Rapid interpersonal bonding reflects the outgoing, affiliative nature of warmth.

items.text: I go out of my way to make newcomers feel included in a group.
items.rationale: Active inclusion behavior toward newcomers is a clear behavioral expression of warmth.

items.text: I am naturally affectionate and enjoy physical expressions of closeness like hugs.
items.rationale: Comfort with and enjoyment of physical affection is a hallmark of high warmth.

items.text: I light up when I see someone I know, and I always greet them enthusiastically.
items.rationale: Enthusiastic social greeting behavior reflects the outgoing, positive interpersonal orientation of warmth.

items.text: I find great satisfaction in helping others feel better when they're going through a hard time.
items.rationale: Deriving satisfaction from emotional support provision reflects the caring, nurturing quality of warmth.

items.text: I prefer spending time with others over being alone; I thrive on human connection.
items.rationale: Strong preference for social contact and connection-seeking is a defining feature of high warmth.

items.text: I am quick to offer a kind word or encouragement to someone who seems down.
items.rationale: Spontaneous verbal kindness toward distressed others reflects the caring, attentive nature of warmth.

items.text: My friends would say I'm one of the most caring and generous people they know.
items.rationale: Third-person attribution of caring and generosity directly reflects high warmth.

items.text: I feel genuinely happy when good things happen to the people around me.
items.rationale: Vicarious joy reflects warmth, though it could also relate to sensitivity's empathic responsiveness.

items.text: I sometimes put others' needs ahead of my own, even when it's not in my best interest.
items.rationale: Self-sacrificing behavior reflects warmth but could also indicate sensitivity or low dominance.

items.text: I feel deeply hurt when someone I care about is going through pain, almost as if it were my own.
items.rationale: While deep empathic connection reflects warmth, the intensity of emotional absorption could map to sensitivity (Factor I).
